{
  "$comment": "Tier 1 of skill detection (docs/signatures.md): flat package-name -> taxonomy slug map. Every key is a normalized package name as ACTUALLY produced by src/import-detect.ts (scope+first-segment for JS, first-dot-segment for Python, first-segment for Ruby, version-stripped path for Go, composer.json's literal keys or PHP `use`'s lowercased first namespace segment; Rust `use`/Cargo.toml crate names with hyphens normalized to underscores; Java/Kotlin `import`/C# `using` roots lowercased at whichever dotted-prefix depth (1-3) is actually a key here — the extractor emits every depth as a candidate, so `com.google.gson`/`com.google.inject` can each get their own 3-segment entry without colliding on the too-generic 2-segment `com.google`, while `org.springframework`/`Microsoft.AspNetCore` stay 2-segment umbrellas on purpose; a handful of JVM libraries (`lombok`, `dagger`) import under a root that's SHORTER than their Maven/Gradle groupId (`org.projectlombok`, `com.google.dagger`) — the map key is always the real IMPORT root, never the groupId, per this file's own dead-key rule below; Swift `import` module names lowercased, or a Package.swift dependency URL's last path segment lowercased) — a Python/Ruby *distribution* name that differs from its *import* name (e.g. PyPI's beautifulsoup4 vs `import bs4`) is a dead key that can never match, not a valid entry. A package deliberately absent here (e.g. @supabase/supabase-js, firebase, @xenova/transformers, axum — already a fully Tier-1-equivalent Tier 2 signature, see docs/signatures.md) is intentionally left to a Tier 2 signature instead, because the bare import doesn't disambiguate which slug applies, or is used for too many unrelated purposes to safely commit to one slug — see docs/signatures.md.",
